		   <tr><td valign="top" id="fs8" class="mform" ><span id="notbold">By:</span> <a href="/db/poster.html?user=124788"><span id=Scholar>Heidii</span></a><b><span id=Scholar><br>Scholar</span></b><br />37 posts
		   <br /><nobr><span id="notbold">Score</span>: Decent [3.00]</nobr><br /><br /><a href="/cgi-bin/pm.pl?action=addtolist&addname=Heidii&type=Address" id="fs8"><img src="/shared/plus.gif" border="0" align="middle" height="9" width="9" alt="Add to address book"> Add to address book</a><br /><img src="/shared/transp.gif" width="135" border="0" height="1"></td><td valign="top" class="mform" width="100%"><p>The damage cap for under 20 caps all weapons at maximum 14 dmg weapons....so an 8 dmg weapon was not actually being &quot;capped&quot; as such under 20, that's why you saw no difference. And strength of 105 won't add much of a strength bonus to your damage output either. As your weapon skill rises in the next few levels you'll get a small increase in damage, but not much off such a low damage weapon. Until you get to level 28 the only increases in damage come from strength and weapon skill increases, and these act like a percentage modifier which is rounded down after being applied...so a 10% increase on a 8 dmg weapon would be 0.8 rounded down to zero...whereas a 10% increase on a 12dmg weapon would be 1.2 rounded down to 1. If you really want to hit harder straight away you're going to have to get a higher damage weapon. Get yourself a Centi short sword for 200-300pp 12/25 and you'll be hitting for 25 at the same speed as the fiber.<br><br><em id=fs8>Edited, Tue Aug 13 09:27:56 2002</em></p></td></td></tr><tr><td colspan="2" class="mform"><table border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" width="100%"><tr><td id="fs8"></td></tr></table>
